1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,500
Here's a question that sounds simple,
but I promise you, it isn't.

2
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:07,500
Are you moving right now?

3
00:00:08,000 --> 00:00:12,000
Your first instinct is probably:
no, obviously not.

4
00:00:12,500 --> 00:00:16,000
But what if I told you
that's completely wrong?

5
00:00:16,500 --> 00:00:22,000
What if you're actually hurtling
through space right now?

6
00:00:22,500 --> 00:00:26,500
The Earth is spinning, and because
you're standing on it, you're spinning too.

7
00:00:27,000 --> 00:00:31,000
At about 1,670 kilometers per hour.

8
00:00:32,000 --> 00:00:35,000
But that's just the beginning.

9
00:00:35,500 --> 00:00:40,000
Earth is orbiting the Sun at
107,000 kilometers per hour.

10
00:00:41,000 --> 00:00:46,000
And our entire solar system is moving
through the Milky Way at 720,000 km/h.

11
00:00:47,000 --> 00:00:52,000
So when someone asks "are you sitting still?"
— it depends what you compare yourself to.

12
00:00:55,500 --> 00:00:59,000
Motion is RELATIVE.

13
00:00:59,500 --> 00:01:03,000
It always depends on your point of view.

14
00:01:03,500 --> 00:01:07,000
Think about a ball sitting
on a moving train.

15
00:01:07,500 --> 00:01:11,000
To someone on the ground—
the ball is clearly moving.

16
00:01:11,500 --> 00:01:15,000
To someone on the train—
the ball is perfectly still.

17
00:01:15,500 --> 00:01:19,500
Same ball. Same moment.
Three different answers.

18
00:01:20,000 --> 00:01:23,000
All three of them are correct.

19
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:28,000
Galileo figured this out
nearly 400 years ago.

20
00:01:29,000 --> 00:01:33,000
A sailor drops a ball
from the top of a ship's mast.

21
00:01:34,000 --> 00:01:39,000
You'd expect the ball to land
behind the mast — but it doesn't.

22
00:01:39,500 --> 00:01:43,000
It lands right at the base.

23
00:01:43,500 --> 00:01:47,500
Because the ball was already
moving with the ship.

24
00:01:48,000 --> 00:01:50,000
This changed physics forever.

25
00:01:51,000 --> 00:01:55,000
You experience relative motion
every day.

26
00:01:56,000 --> 00:02:01,000
Walking at 5 km/h inside a plane
going 900 km/h?

27
00:02:01,500 --> 00:02:05,500
Your speed relative to ground:
905 km/h!

28
00:02:07,000 --> 00:02:12,000
Driving at 100 km/h next to a car
at the same speed?

29
00:02:12,500 --> 00:02:16,000
That car looks completely still to you.

30
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:23,000
The Moon is constantly falling
toward Earth, pulled by gravity.

31
00:02:23,500 --> 00:02:28,000
But it's moving sideways so fast
it keeps missing.

32
00:02:28,500 --> 00:02:31,000
That's what an orbit is.

33
00:02:35,500 --> 00:02:39,000
1. Motion is always RELATIVE
to a reference frame.

34
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:44,000
2. There is NO absolute motion
in the universe.

35
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:49,000
3. Even "standing still" is
a choice of perspective.

36
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:57,000
Einstein built his entire theory
of relativity on this idea.

37
00:02:58,000 --> 00:03:00,000
Now you understand it too.

